    "shortDesc": "Hypersecretion of calcitonin",
    "longDesc": "Hypersecretion of calcitonin",
    "plainEnglish": "Your thyroid gland is producing too much calcitonin, a hormone that helps regulate calcium levels in your blood. This overproduction can occur due to a thyroid condition or, rarely, from a tumor that produces calcitonin. While calcitonin itself helps lower blood calcium when it's too high, excessive amounts may cause symptoms like flushing, diarrhea, or joint pain, though many people have no symptoms at all.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists and general physicians use this code when evaluating patients with elevated calcitonin levels, often as part of screening for medullary thyroid cancer or investigating thyroid disorders. It appears on EOB statements when calcitonin testing is performed or when a thyroid condition causing hormone overproduction is documented.",
