    "shortDesc": "Dyshormogenetic goiter",
    "longDesc": "Dyshormogenetic goiter",
    "plainEnglish": "Dyshormogenetic goiter is an enlarged thyroid gland caused by a genetic defect that prevents your thyroid from properly producing thyroid hormones, even though the gland itself is working hard to try to make them. This inherited condition can range from mild to severe and may cause symptoms like neck swelling, fatigue, or problems with metabolism and growth, depending on how much thyroid hormone your body is actually able to produce.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists and pediatricians diagnose and manage dyshormogenetic goiter, typically in children or young adults who present with thyroid enlargement and abnormal thyroid function tests. This code appears on EOB statements when patients undergo thyroid imaging, blood tests, or specialist consultations for evaluation of congenital thyroid hormone synthesis disorders.",
