    "rawCode": "E0781",
    "shortDesc": "Sick-euthyroid syndrome",
    "longDesc": "Sick-euthyroid syndrome",
    "plainEnglish": "Sick-euthyroid syndrome is a condition where your thyroid blood tests appear normal (euthyroid means normal thyroid function), but you have symptoms that suggest thyroid problems because your body is not handling thyroid hormones properly due to another serious illness or stress. This typically happens during severe infections, major surgery, trauma, or other critical illnesses that interfere with how your thyroid hormones are converted and used by your body, even though your thyroid gland itself is working normally.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists, internists, and critical care physicians use this code when treating hospitalized or seriously ill patients who show abnormal thyroid hormone levels during acute illness. It may appear on EOB statements for patients in intensive care settings or those recovering from major surgery or severe infections, though it's more common in hospital billing than outpatient claims.",
