    "shortDesc": "Drug/chem diabetes mellitus w oth diabetic arthropathy",
    "longDesc": "Drug or chemical induced diabetes mellitus with other diabetic arthropathy",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes diabetes that was caused by taking certain medications or being exposed to harmful chemicals, and the person has also developed joint pain or damage related to that diabetes. While most diabetes is either type 1 or type 2, some medications (like steroids) or chemical exposures can actually cause diabetes to develop. When this medication-induced diabetes damages the joints—causing pain, stiffness, or arthritis-like symptoms—this specific code is used to capture both the diabetes and the joint problem together.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists, rheumatologists, primary care physicians, and hospital providers use this code when treating patients whose diabetes resulted from medication side effects or occupational/environmental chemical exposure and who also have diabetic joint complications. This code appears on EOB statements when a patient's diabetes is directly attributed to a drug or chemical cause rather than the typical type 1 or type 2 classification.",
