    "plainEnglish": "This code describes diabetes that developed as a result of taking certain medications or being exposed to harmful chemicals, and the patient also has a skin condition (dermatitis) caused by the diabetes. Unlike type 1 or type 2 diabetes that develop on their own, this type of diabetes is a known side effect of specific drugs or chemical exposures—examples include certain steroids, some psychiatric medications, or occupational chemical exposure. The skin condition that accompanies it causes inflammation, itching, and irritation, often appearing in areas prone to moisture or friction.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists, primary care physicians, dermatologists, and occupational medicine specialists use this code when treating patients whose diabetes was triggered by medication side effects or chemical exposure and who also present with diabetic skin complications. This code appears on EOB statements when a patient is being treated for both the medication-induced diabetes and the resulting skin manifestation in outpatient or hospital settings.",
