    "plainEnglish": "This code means you've developed diabetes as a side effect of taking a medication or being exposed to a harmful chemical. Unlike type 1 or type 2 diabetes that develop on their own, this type of diabetes is directly caused by something you've been given or exposed to—such as certain steroids, anti-psychotic medications, or industrial chemicals. You may experience typical diabetes symptoms like increased thirst, frequent urination, and fatigue, and your blood sugar will need to be monitored and managed even after the medication or exposure stops.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists, primary care physicians, and specialists prescribing medications known to cause hyperglycemia use this code when documenting drug-induced diabetes. It commonly appears on EOB statements when patients develop diabetes following treatment with corticosteroids, atypical antipsychotics, or other glucose-raising medications, and helps distinguish this secondary cause from primary diabetes types for treatment and prognosis purposes.",
    "billable": true,
    "isNew": false,
    "isRevised": false,
