    "code": "E10.10",
    "rawCode": "E1010",
    "shortDesc": "Type 1 diabetes mellitus with ketoacidosis without coma",
    "longDesc": "Type 1 diabetes mellitus with ketoacidosis without coma",
    "plainEnglish": "Type 1 diabetes is a condition where your pancreas can't make insulin, a hormone your body needs to control blood sugar. Ketoacidosis is a serious complication that happens when your blood becomes too acidic because your body is breaking down fat too quickly for energy, usually triggered by infection, illness, or missed insulin doses. You may experience nausea, vomiting, rapid breathing, fruity-smelling breath, and confusion, but you're still alert and conscious (not in a coma)—this is a medical emergency that requires immediate hospital care.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists, emergency medicine physicians, and hospitalists use this code when treating patients with Type 1 diabetes presenting with ketoacidosis. It commonly appears on hospital bills and emergency department claims but is less frequent on routine outpatient EOBs since it indicates an acute, serious condition requiring acute care.",
