    "rawCode": "E1029",
    "shortDesc": "Type 1 diabetes mellitus w oth diabetic kidney complication",
    "longDesc": "Type 1 diabetes mellitus with other diabetic kidney complication",
    "plainEnglish": "Type 1 diabetes has damaged your kidneys in a way that isn't covered by the more common complications like protein leakage or early-stage kidney disease. This means your pancreas doesn't make insulin (which is what causes type 1 diabetes), and your blood sugar has been high enough over time to affect kidney function in a less typical way—perhaps involving kidney inflammation, scarring, or other changes that your doctor found during testing. You'll likely need to monitor your kidney function closely with regular blood tests and adjust your diabetes management to protect what kidney function remains.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists and nephrologists (kidney specialists) use this code when managing type 1 diabetic patients with kidney involvement beyond the standard diabetic nephropathy stages. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients requiring ongoing kidney monitoring, specialist visits, or treatment adjustments related to their diabetes.",
