    "shortDesc": "Type 1 diabetes mellitus with diabetic cataract",
    "longDesc": "Type 1 diabetes mellitus with diabetic cataract",
    "plainEnglish": "Type 1 diabetes has damaged the lens of your eye, causing it to become cloudy—a condition called a cataract. This happens when high blood sugar over time triggers chemical changes that make the lens lose its transparency, leading to blurry or dimmed vision. If left untreated, cataracts can significantly interfere with your ability to see clearly and may eventually require surgery to restore vision.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists, ophthalmologists, and primary care physicians use this code when documenting diabetes-related eye complications in patients with type 1 diabetes. It commonly appears on patient EOB statements when someone with type 1 diabetes undergoes eye exams or cataract procedures, as it links the vision problem directly to their underlying diabetes.",
