    "code": "E10.40",
    "rawCode": "E1040",
    "shortDesc": "Type 1 diabetes mellitus with diabetic neuropathy, unsp",
    "longDesc": "Type 1 diabetes mellitus with diabetic neuropathy, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a complication of type 1 diabetes where high blood sugar levels have damaged the nerves in your body, causing a condition called neuropathy. People with this condition often experience numbness, tingling, pain, or weakness—typically starting in the feet and hands—because the nerve damage interferes with how sensations are transmitted. This is a serious long-term complication that can develop over years of living with diabetes, especially if blood sugar levels haven't been well controlled.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists, primary care physicians, and neurologists use this code when documenting diabetic complications. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients with type 1 diabetes who have developed nerve damage and are undergoing treatment, monitoring, or management of their neuropathic symptoms.",
