    "plainEnglish": "Type 1 diabetes has damaged a single nerve in your body, causing weakness, pain, or numbness in that specific area. This happens when high blood sugar levels injure the nerve's protective covering over time. You might notice tingling, burning, or weakness in your hand, foot, or another location where that nerve controls sensation or movement.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists, primary care physicians, and neurologists use this code when documenting diabetic nerve damage affecting one nerve. It commonly appears on EOBs for patients with established Type 1 diabetes who develop nerve complications, typically triggering specialist referrals and nerve-specific treatments.",
