    "longDesc": "Type 1 diabetes mellitus with diabetic peripheral angiopathy without gangrene",
    "plainEnglish": "Type 1 diabetes mellitus with diabetic peripheral angiopathy without gangrene means your blood vessels in your legs and feet have been damaged by diabetes, reducing blood flow to these areas, but gangrene (tissue death) has not yet developed. This condition occurs when high blood sugar levels over time weaken and narrow the arteries that supply your legs and feet, which can cause pain, numbness, slow-healing sores, or cramping when you walk. Without proper management, this vascular damage increases your risk of serious complications, which is why your doctor is monitoring it closely.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists, primary care physicians, cardiologists, and vascular surgeons use this code when treating Type 1 diabetic patients with peripheral vascular disease. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients with long-standing diabetes who require ongoing management of circulation problems and may need vascular studies, specialist consultations, or preventive treatments.",
