    "longDesc": "Type 1 diabetes mellitus with hypoglycemia without coma",
    "plainEnglish": "Type 1 diabetes is a condition where your pancreas cannot produce insulin, the hormone needed to regulate blood sugar. Hypoglycemia means your blood sugar has dropped dangerously low (usually below 70 mg/dL), which can cause symptoms like shakiness, sweating, confusion, or rapid heartbeat—but you remain conscious and alert. This code indicates you experienced low blood sugar related to your Type 1 diabetes without losing consciousness.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists, primary care physicians, and emergency medicine doctors use this code when treating Type 1 diabetic patients with documented low blood sugar episodes. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients who seek urgent care or emergency department visits for hypoglycemia management, as well as for hospital admissions and follow-up office visits focused on diabetes control.",
