    "shortDesc": "Type 1 diabetes mellitus, presymptomatic, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Type 1 diabetes mellitus, presymptomatic, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a situation where someone has been identified as having type 1 diabetes, but they haven't yet shown any symptoms of the disease. Type 1 diabetes is an autoimmune condition where the body's immune system attacks the cells in the pancreas that produce insulin, a hormone needed to control blood sugar. In the presymptomatic stage, blood tests (often checking for diabetes-related antibodies) have confirmed the disease is developing, but the person may feel completely fine and have normal blood sugar levels because enough insulin-producing cells are still functioning.",
