    "rawCode": "E1140",
    "shortDesc": "Type 2 diabetes mellitus with diabetic neuropathy, unsp",
    "longDesc": "Type 2 diabetes mellitus with diabetic neuropathy, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a person with type 2 diabetes whose high blood sugar has damaged the nerves in their body, causing weakness, numbness, pain, or tingling—usually starting in the feet and hands. Diabetic neuropathy happens when consistently elevated glucose levels harm the protective coating around nerves, and the person either hasn't been fully tested yet or doesn't fit into a more specific nerve damage category.",
    "whoUses": "Primary care doctors, endocrinologists, and neurologists use this code when managing diabetes complications. It commonly appears on patient EOB statements as it's a frequent complication of type 2 diabetes and may lead to additional testing, specialist referrals, or changed treatment plans.",
