    "code": "E11.41",
    "rawCode": "E1141",
    "shortDesc": "Type 2 diabetes mellitus with diabetic mononeuropathy",
    "longDesc": "Type 2 diabetes mellitus with diabetic mononeuropathy",
    "plainEnglish": "Type 2 diabetes mellitus with diabetic mononeuropathy means that your diabetes has damaged a single nerve in your body, causing weakness, pain, or loss of sensation in that specific area. This happens when high blood sugar levels over time harm the protective coating around nerve fibers, and unlike other diabetic nerve damage that affects multiple nerves, mononeuropathy affects just one nerve—commonly in the face, arm, or leg. You might experience sudden weakness in one eye, wrist drop, or numbness and tingling in one specific location.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists, neurologists, and primary care physicians use this code when documenting diabetes complications in patients with isolated nerve damage. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients with type 2 diabetes who develop focal nerve injuries, particularly when neurological testing or imaging confirms single-nerve involvement.",
