    "plainEnglish": "Type 2 diabetes has damaged the nerves in your body, causing a condition called polyneuropathy. This means multiple nerves are affected, typically in your feet and hands, and you may experience numbness, tingling, burning sensations, or weakness. This nerve damage develops over time when high blood sugar levels harm the protective covering of nerves, and it's one of the common complications that can occur in people with type 2 diabetes.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists, primary care physicians, and neurologists use this code when managing diabetes patients who develop nerve damage. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients with long-standing type 2 diabetes who present with symptoms of neuropathy or are being monitored for this complication.",
