    "longDesc": "Type 2 diabetes mellitus without complications in remission",
    "plainEnglish": "Type 2 diabetes is a condition where your body has trouble managing blood sugar levels, usually because it doesn't use insulin effectively. This code means you have type 2 diabetes that is currently in remission—meaning your blood sugar levels have returned to normal or near-normal ranges, often through diet, exercise, weight loss, or medication—and you don't currently have any serious complications from the disease like kidney damage, vision problems, or nerve damage. However, you still have the underlying diabetes diagnosis, so your doctor will continue to monitor you.",
    "whoUses": "Primary care physicians (internists and family medicine doctors), endocrinologists, and diabetes specialists use this code when documenting patients whose diabetes is well-controlled and in remission. This code appears on patient EOBs when they receive diabetes management visits or lab work to monitor their remission status, though it's more commonly seen in provider records than on patient-facing statements.",
