    "rawCode": "E215",
    "shortDesc": "Disorder of parathyroid gland, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Disorder of parathyroid gland, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "This code is used when a doctor has identified that your parathyroid glands (small glands in your neck that control calcium levels) aren't working properly, but the specific problem hasn't been pinpointed or fully diagnosed yet. Your parathyroid glands may be producing too much or too little parathyroid hormone, which can cause your calcium levels to be abnormal and lead to symptoms like weakness, bone pain, or kidney problems. This is typically a temporary coding choice while your doctor is still investigating what's actually wrong with your parathyroids.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists and primary care physicians use this code when parathyroid dysfunction is suspected but not yet specifically identified—often appearing during initial workup or when test results are unclear. It commonly appears on EOB statements as a preliminary diagnosis code before being refined to a more specific parathyroid condition.",
