    "code": "E22.2",
    "rawCode": "E222",
    "shortDesc": "Syndrome of inappropriate secretion of antidiuretic hormone",
    "longDesc": "Syndrome of inappropriate secretion of antidiuretic hormone",
    "plainEnglish": "This condition occurs when your body produces too much antidiuretic hormone (ADH), a substance that controls how much water your kidneys retain. When ADH levels are abnormally high, your kidneys hold onto excess water, causing sodium levels in your blood to drop and leading to swelling, confusion, seizures, or fatigue. This can happen as a side effect of certain medications, lung infections, head injuries, or various cancers, and requires treatment to restore proper fluid and electrolyte balance.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists, internists, and hospitalists commonly use this code when diagnosing and managing patients with SIADH, particularly those with cancer, infections, or medication-related causes. This code frequently appears on EOB statements for patients requiring hospital stays or specialist consultations for electrolyte imbalances.",
