    "plainEnglish": "Hypopituitarism means your pituitary gland—a small gland at the base of your brain that controls many important hormones—is not producing enough of one or more hormones. This can result in deficiencies of growth hormone, thyroid hormone, cortisol, or sex hormones, leading to symptoms like fatigue, weight changes, low blood pressure, or sexual dysfunction depending on which hormones are affected. The condition can develop from a tumor, head injury, surgery, radiation, or sometimes no clear cause.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists primarily diagnose and manage hypopituitarism, though primary care doctors, neurologists (if a tumor is involved), and other specialists may be involved in treatment. This code commonly appears on EOB statements when patients undergo hormone replacement therapy or pituitary function testing.",
