    "longDesc": "Drug-induced hypopituitarism",
    "plainEnglish": "This diagnosis means your pituitary gland (a small gland at the base of your brain that controls many hormones) is not producing enough hormones because of a medication you're taking. Certain drugs—such as some antipsychotics, opioids, dopamine antagonists, or other medications—can interfere with how your pituitary works and lower your hormone levels. Depending on which hormones are affected, you might experience fatigue, low sex drive, mood changes, or other symptoms related to hormone deficiency.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists and primary care physicians use this code when treating patients whose pituitary hormone deficiency is clearly linked to medication use. It commonly appears on EOB statements when patients develop hormonal problems after starting new medications, and the doctor needs to distinguish drug-induced deficiency from other pituitary disorders for treatment planning and possible medication adjustment.",
