    "shortDesc": "Diabetes insipidus",
    "longDesc": "Diabetes insipidus",
    "plainEnglish": "Diabetes insipidus is a rare condition where your body either doesn't produce enough antidiuretic hormone (ADH)—a chemical that helps your kidneys retain water—or your kidneys don't respond properly to it. This causes you to produce abnormally large amounts of dilute urine and feel intensely thirsty, even though this is a completely different condition from the more common type 1 or type 2 diabetes (which involve blood sugar problems). If untreated, it can lead to severe dehydration and electrolyte imbalances.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists and internists commonly diagnose and manage this condition, and it may occasionally appear on patient EOBs when someone undergoes testing or treatment for excessive thirst and urination. Emergency department physicians also use this code when patients present with acute dehydration related to uncontrolled diabetes insipidus.",
