    "shortDesc": "Pituitary-dependent Cushing's disease",
    "longDesc": "Pituitary-dependent Cushing's disease",
    "plainEnglish": "Cushing's disease occurs when a small tumor in your pituitary gland (located at the base of your brain) produces too much of a hormone that signals your adrenal glands to make excess cortisol. This overproduction of cortisol causes a cluster of symptoms including weight gain (especially in the face and upper back), purple stretch marks, easy bruising, muscle weakness, mood changes, and high blood pressure. It's different from other forms of Cushing's syndrome because the problem originates in the pituitary gland rather than in the adrenal glands themselves or from taking steroid medications.",
