    "plainEnglish": "Nelson's syndrome is a rare hormonal disorder that can develop after surgical removal of the adrenal glands (usually done to treat Cushing's syndrome). When the adrenal glands are removed, the pituitary gland loses its normal feedback signal and begins producing excessive amounts of ACTH (a hormone that normally stimulates the adrenal glands), leading to high cortisol levels, darkening of the skin, and other hormonal imbalances. Patients may experience progressive darkening of the skin, muscle weakness, mood changes, and vision problems if a pituitary tumor develops.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists primarily diagnose and manage Nelson's syndrome in patients with a history of bilateral adrenalectomy for Cushing's syndrome treatment. While this is a specialized diagnosis, it may appear on EOB statements for patients receiving ongoing endocrine care, imaging studies, or pituitary monitoring.",
    "billable": true,
