    "longDesc": "Drug-induced Cushing's syndrome",
    "plainEnglish": "This diagnosis means you've developed Cushing's syndrome—a condition where your body has too much cortisol (a stress hormone)—specifically because of a medication you're taking. Rather than your body producing excess cortisol on its own, certain drugs (most commonly steroids like prednisone, or other medications) are causing your cortisol levels to rise abnormally high. You might experience symptoms like weight gain in the face and upper back, purple stretch marks, easy bruising, muscle weakness, or mood changes.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists, internal medicine doctors, and primary care physicians use this code when diagnosing patients whose steroid or other medication use has triggered Cushing's syndrome. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients on long-term corticosteroid therapy who develop these complications, and is important to distinguish from other causes of Cushing's syndrome because the treatment involves adjusting or stopping the offending medication rather than surgery or other interventions.",
