    "plainEnglish": "Secondary hyperaldosteronism means your body is producing too much of a hormone called aldosterone, but this is happening as a result of another underlying condition rather than a problem with your adrenal glands themselves. Common causes include kidney disease, liver cirrhosis, heart failure, or high blood pressure, which trigger your body to make extra aldosterone in an attempt to regulate fluid and salt balance. You might experience symptoms like high blood pressure, weakness, muscle cramps, or swelling, depending on what's causing the excess aldosterone production.",
