    "shortDesc": "Primary adrenocortical insufficiency",
    "longDesc": "Primary adrenocortical insufficiency",
    "plainEnglish": "Primary adrenocortical insufficiency, also called Addison's disease, means your adrenal glands (small glands on top of your kidneys) aren't producing enough of the hormones cortisol and aldosterone that your body needs. This can happen because the adrenal glands are damaged or destroyed by infection, autoimmune disease, bleeding, or cancer, and it causes symptoms like severe fatigue, low blood pressure, weight loss, and darkening of the skin. Without treatment, this condition can be life-threatening, but it's manageable with hormone replacement therapy.",
