    "shortDesc": "Multiple endocrine neoplasia [MEN] syndrome, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Multiple endocrine neoplasia [MEN] syndrome, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "Multiple endocrine neoplasia (MEN) is a genetic condition where a person develops tumors in multiple glands that produce hormones, but the specific type hasn't been identified or documented in detail. These tumors can form in the pancreas, pituitary gland, parathyroid glands, and other hormone-producing organs, causing various hormone imbalances and health complications. Symptoms depend on which glands are affected and can range from high calcium levels and kidney stones to digestive problems and hormonal irregularities.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists, oncologists, and genetic specialists use this code when evaluating patients with multiple hormone-producing tumors suspected to be from an MEN syndrome but the specific type (MEN 1, 2A, or 2B) hasn't been confirmed yet. This code commonly appears on EOB statements during initial diagnosis and ongoing management while the exact MEN type is being determined through genetic testing and imaging studies.",
