    "plainEnglish": "Your thymus gland, which is located in your chest and normally shrinks after childhood, has remained abnormally enlarged or continued to grow when it should have gotten smaller. This condition, called persistent hyperplasia of the thymus, means the gland didn't follow the typical pattern of shrinking with age. While the thymus plays a role in immune system development, an oversized thymus can sometimes cause breathing difficulties, chest discomfort, or be discovered incidentally on imaging done for other reasons.",
    "whoUses": "Pediatricians, internists, and thoracic surgeons typically encounter this code, often discovered on chest X-rays or CT scans in children or young adults. It appears less commonly on patient EOB statements unless the condition required specific imaging studies or surgical evaluation, as it may be an incidental finding rather than a condition requiring active treatment.",
