    "code": "E40",
    "rawCode": "E40",
    "shortDesc": "Kwashiorkor",
    "longDesc": "Kwashiorkor",
    "plainEnglish": "Kwashiorkor is a severe form of protein malnutrition that occurs when someone doesn't eat enough protein-rich foods, even though they may be consuming adequate calories from carbohydrates or fats. This condition causes fluid retention in the belly and legs, muscle wasting, weak immunity, and stunted growth, and is most common in young children in areas where food is scarce or poverty limits access to nutritious proteins like meat, eggs, and beans.",
    "whoUses": "Pediatricians, nutritionists, and public health specialists use this code, primarily in developing countries or in clinical settings treating malnourished children. It rarely appears on EOB statements in developed nations except in cases of severe neglect or unusual medical circumstances, as it is largely preventable with adequate nutrition access.",
    "billable": true,
    "isNew": false,
    "isRevised": false,
