    "code": "E41",
    "rawCode": "E41",
    "shortDesc": "Nutritional marasmus",
    "longDesc": "Nutritional marasmus",
    "plainEnglish": "Nutritional marasmus is severe malnutrition and wasting of the body caused by not getting enough calories and protein over a prolonged period. This condition causes the body to break down its own muscle and fat for energy, resulting in extreme weight loss, weakness, and a skeletal appearance. It's most commonly seen in infants and young children in areas with food scarcity, but can also occur in adults who are severely malnourished due to poverty, illness, or inability to eat.",
    "whoUses": "Pediatricians, family medicine doctors, and hospitalists use this code when treating malnourished children, particularly in developing countries or during malnutrition screenings. It appears less commonly on routine patient EOBs in developed nations but may show up for patients with severe eating disorders, chronic illness, or documented food insecurity being addressed during hospital or clinic visits.",
