    "shortDesc": "Vitamin A deficiency with conjunctival xerosis",
    "longDesc": "Vitamin A deficiency with conjunctival xerosis",
    "plainEnglish": "Vitamin A deficiency with conjunctival xerosis means your body doesn't have enough vitamin A, which is causing your eyes to become abnormally dry. This happens because vitamin A is essential for maintaining the protective moisture layer on the surface of your eyes; without it, the clear membrane covering the white of your eye (the conjunctiva) dries out. You might experience eye discomfort, grittiness, blurred vision, or sensitivity to light, and if left untreated, this condition can eventually lead to corneal damage and vision problems.",
    "whoUses": "Ophthalmologists and optometrists primarily use this code when evaluating patients with dry eye conditions related to vitamin A deficiency, often in the context of nutritional assessment or international health settings. It may also appear on EOB statements for patients receiving treatment for severe dry eye syndrome with documented nutritional deficiency.",
