    "rawCode": "E611",
    "shortDesc": "Iron deficiency",
    "longDesc": "Iron deficiency",
    "plainEnglish": "Iron deficiency means your body doesn't have enough iron to make healthy red blood cells, which carry oxygen throughout your body. This can happen because you're not eating enough iron-rich foods, your body isn't absorbing iron properly, or you're losing blood (from heavy periods, digestive issues, or other causes). You might feel tired, weak, short of breath, or notice pale skin or brittle nails.",
    "whoUses": "Primary care physicians, internal medicine doctors, hematologists, and gastroenterologists commonly use this code when diagnosing the underlying cause of low iron levels. It appears regularly on patient EOBs when iron studies or blood tests reveal deficiency, often leading to further workup to determine the source of iron loss.",
