    "longDesc": "Manganese deficiency",
    "plainEnglish": "Manganese deficiency means your body doesn't have enough manganese, a mineral that helps with bone health, wound healing, and metabolism. While rare in people eating a normal diet, this deficiency can develop in those on long-term intravenous nutrition, certain digestive disorders, or specific medications that interfere with mineral absorption. You might experience weak bones, joint problems, slow wound healing, or skin issues, though symptoms are often subtle.",
    "whoUses": "Nutritionists, gastroenterologists, and hospitalists commonly code this condition, particularly in patients on long-term parenteral nutrition (IV feeding). This code appears infrequently on patient EOBs since manganese deficiency is relatively uncommon and often addressed through nutrition supplementation rather than standalone treatment.",
