    "plainEnglish": "This code describes lasting health problems that remain after someone has recovered from severe malnutrition—a condition where the body didn't get enough calories and protein to function properly. Even though the person may no longer be malnourished, their body continues to experience long-term effects such as stunted growth, weakened muscles, organ damage, or developmental delays. These 'sequelae' (aftereffects) can persist for years and may require ongoing medical care and monitoring.",
    "whoUses": "This code is primarily used by primary care physicians, pediatricians, and nutritionists when evaluating patients with lingering consequences of past malnutrition, particularly in children from developing countries or patients with severe eating disorders. It appears on EOBs when documenting chronic complications from malnutrition rather than the acute malnutrition itself, and is less commonly seen in routine outpatient care than codes for active nutritional deficiencies.",
    "billable": true,
    "isNew": false,
    "isRevised": false,
