    "plainEnglish": "This code describes weight gain and obesity that develops as a side effect of taking certain medications. Some drugs—like certain antipsychotics, corticosteroids, antidepressants, or diabetes medications—can increase appetite, slow metabolism, or cause your body to retain water and fat, leading to significant weight gain. If your doctor believes your obesity is directly caused by a medication you're taking, they may use this code rather than a general obesity code.",
    "whoUses": "Primary care physicians, psychiatrists, endocrinologists, and cardiologists use this code when documenting obesity that is clearly linked to medication side effects. It appears on EOB statements when patients are being treated for medication-related weight gain, and it's particularly common in records for patients on antipsychotics, steroids, or other appetite-stimulating drugs.",
