    "longDesc": "Morbid (severe) obesity with alveolar hypoventilation",
    "plainEnglish": "This diagnosis describes severe obesity combined with a serious breathing problem where your lungs don't move enough air in and out (shallow breathing). The extra weight from severe obesity puts pressure on your chest and diaphragm, making it harder for your body to get enough oxygen and remove carbon dioxide, a condition sometimes called Pickwickian syndrome. You might experience daytime sleepiness, shortness of breath, headaches, and a bluish tint to your skin or lips.",
    "whoUses": "Pulmonologists, sleep medicine specialists, bariatric surgeons, and primary care physicians use this code when managing patients with severe obesity causing respiratory compromise. It commonly appears in hospital settings and sleep clinics for patients requiring oxygen therapy or mechanical ventilation, and may show on EOB statements when sleep studies, breathing tests, or obesity-related treatments are documented.",
