    "rawCode": "E670",
    "shortDesc": "Hypervitaminosis A",
    "longDesc": "Hypervitaminosis A",
    "plainEnglish": "Hypervitaminosis A means you have too much vitamin A in your body, which has built up to toxic levels. This can happen from taking excessive vitamin A supplements or, rarely, from eating very large amounts of vitamin A-rich foods like liver. Too much vitamin A can cause symptoms like nausea, headaches, dry skin, hair loss, and in severe cases, liver damage and bone problems.",
    "whoUses": "Dermatologists, primary care physicians, and toxicologists use this code when diagnosing vitamin A toxicity, typically in patients who have been taking high-dose supplements without medical supervision. It appears on EOB statements when a patient seeks treatment for symptoms of vitamin A overdose and requires blood work or imaging to confirm the diagnosis.",
