    "shortDesc": "Tyrosinemia",
    "longDesc": "Tyrosinemia",
    "plainEnglish": "Tyrosinemia is a rare inherited metabolic disorder where your body cannot properly break down the amino acid tyrosine (a building block of protein), causing it to accumulate to toxic levels in your blood and tissues. This buildup can damage multiple organs, especially the liver and kidneys, leading to symptoms like jaundice (yellowing of skin), poor growth, intellectual disability, and in severe cases, liver failure. The condition is present from birth and requires special dietary management and sometimes medication to help your body process tyrosine more effectively.",
    "whoUses": "Pediatricians, metabolic disorder specialists (geneticists), hepatologists, and nephologists use this code when diagnosing and managing children with tyrosinemia. It commonly appears on EOB statements for affected families because the condition requires ongoing specialized care, genetic testing, and dietary management throughout the patient's life.",
