    "code": "E71.2",
    "rawCode": "E712",
    "shortDesc": "Disorder of branched-chain amino-acid metabolism, unsp",
    "longDesc": "Disorder of branched-chain amino-acid metabolism, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "Your body has trouble breaking down certain amino acids (building blocks of protein) called branched-chain amino acids, which include leucine, isoleucine, and valine. These amino acids normally get processed through specific metabolic pathways, but when these pathways don't work properly, the amino acids can build up in your blood and tissues, potentially causing developmental delays, muscle weakness, or neurological problems. The 'unspecified' part means your doctor hasn't identified which particular branched-chain amino acid disorder you have, or testing hasn't pinpointed the exact type yet.",
    "whoUses": "Metabolic specialists, genetic counselors, pediatricians, and neurologists use this code when evaluating patients with suspected branched-chain amino acid metabolism disorders, often during newborn screening follow-up or when a patient presents with developmental concerns. This code typically appears on EOBs for genetic testing, metabolic workup, or specialist consultations but is relatively uncommon in routine primary care.",
