    "shortDesc": "Long chain/very long chain acyl CoA dehydrogenase deficiency",
    "longDesc": "Long chain/very long chain acyl CoA dehydrogenase deficiency",
    "plainEnglish": "Long chain/very long chain acyl CoA dehydrogenase deficiency is a rare genetic metabolic disorder where your body cannot properly break down certain fatty acids for energy. This causes fatty acids to build up in your muscles, heart, and other organs, which can lead to muscle weakness, heart problems, low blood sugar, and liver damage—especially during illness, fasting, or exercise when your body needs to burn fat for fuel. Symptoms typically appear in infancy or early childhood and can range from mild to life-threatening depending on the severity of the enzyme deficiency.",
    "whoUses": "This code is used by pediatric metabolic specialists, cardiologists, and geneticists who diagnose and manage inherited fatty acid oxidation disorders. It commonly appears on EOBs for children receiving genetic testing, specialized metabolic evaluations, and ongoing disease management, though it is relatively rare in the general population.",
