    "shortDesc": "Medium chain acyl CoA dehydrogenase deficiency",
    "longDesc": "Medium chain acyl CoA dehydrogenase deficiency",
    "plainEnglish": "Medium chain acyl CoA dehydrogenase (MCAD) deficiency is a rare inherited metabolic disorder where your body cannot properly break down certain fats for energy, particularly medium-length fatty acid chains. When you fast or become ill, your body normally switches to burning stored fat for fuel, but people with MCAD deficiency struggle to do this efficiently, which can lead to dangerously low blood sugar, liver problems, and muscle weakness. Symptoms typically appear in infancy or early childhood and may include unusual sleepiness, vomiting, seizures, or developmental delays.",
    "whoUses": "Pediatricians, metabolic disorder specialists (metabolic or genetic medicine physicians), and neonatal intensive care doctors use this code, as MCAD deficiency is typically identified through newborn screening programs or when a child develops symptoms. This code occasionally appears on EOBs for parents seeking reimbursement for specialized metabolic testing, genetic counseling, or follow-up care management.",
