    "shortDesc": "Rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata",
    "longDesc": "Rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata",
    "plainEnglish": "Rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata is a rare genetic bone disorder where a child is born with shortened limbs (especially the upper arms and thighs), characteristic bone patterns with small dots or stippling visible on X-rays, and often developmental delays or intellectual disability. The condition is inherited and affects how bones develop and grow before birth, resulting in distinctive physical features and varying levels of disability depending on the severity.",
    "whoUses": "This code is primarily used by pediatricians, geneticists, orthopedic specialists, and clinical geneticists who diagnose and manage this rare inherited metabolic disorder in children. It appears less commonly on patient EOBs since it's a rare congenital condition typically diagnosed in infancy, but when present, it reflects ongoing specialized care and monitoring.",
