    "rawCode": "E7202",
    "shortDesc": "Hartnup's disease",
    "longDesc": "Hartnup's disease",
    "plainEnglish": "Hartnup's disease is a rare inherited condition where your body cannot properly absorb certain amino acids (the building blocks of proteins) from food, particularly tryptophan. This causes these amino acids to be lost in your urine instead of being used by your body. Symptoms can include a rash that appears after sun exposure, diarrhea, and sometimes neurological problems like confusion or poor coordination, though some people with the condition have no symptoms at all.",
    "whoUses": "Geneticists, metabolic disorder specialists, and pediatricians typically diagnose and manage Hartnup's disease, often after newborn screening or when a patient develops characteristic symptoms. This code appears less frequently on EOB statements since it's a rare genetic condition, but will be used when a patient with this diagnosis receives testing, genetic counseling, or treatment for related complications.",
