    "code": "E72.04",
    "rawCode": "E7204",
    "shortDesc": "Cystinosis",
    "longDesc": "Cystinosis",
    "plainEnglish": "Cystinosis is a rare inherited metabolic disorder where a protein called cystine builds up abnormally in your cells and tissues, particularly in the kidneys, eyes, and other organs. This buildup happens because your body lacks an enzyme that normally breaks down and removes cystine, leading to crystal formation that can damage these organs over time and cause symptoms like excessive thirst, kidney problems, and eye sensitivity to light. If you have this diagnosis, it means genetic testing likely confirmed this condition, and you'll need ongoing monitoring and specialized treatment to slow organ damage.",
    "whoUses": "Metabolic disease specialists, nephrologists (kidney doctors), pediatricians, and ophthalmologists manage cystinosis, as it often appears in children and requires multidisciplinary care. This code commonly appears on EOBs when patients receive genetic testing, kidney function monitoring, eye exams, or medication management (such as cysteamine therapy) for this lifelong condition.",
