    "code": "E72.10",
    "rawCode": "E7210",
    "shortDesc": "Disorders of sulfur-bearing amino-acid metabolism, unsp",
    "longDesc": "Disorders of sulfur-bearing amino-acid metabolism, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "Your body uses amino acids (building blocks of protein) that contain sulfur to make important proteins and other molecules. When something goes wrong with how your body processes these sulfur-containing amino acids, it's called a disorder of sulfur-bearing amino-acid metabolism. This code is used when doctors know you have this type of metabolic problem but haven't identified the specific type yet—it could involve amino acids like methionine or cysteine, which your body needs for proper functioning.",
    "whoUses": "Metabolic specialists, geneticists, and biochemical geneticists use this code during initial diagnosis or workup of suspected amino acid metabolism disorders. It may appear on EOB statements when patients undergo specialized testing or genetic evaluation for unexplained developmental delays, neurological symptoms, or abnormal amino acid screening results.",
