    "code": "E72.20",
    "rawCode": "E7220",
    "shortDesc": "Disorder of urea cycle metabolism, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Disorder of urea cycle metabolism, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "A urea cycle disorder means your body has difficulty breaking down and removing ammonia, a toxic waste product from protein metabolism. These inherited conditions affect enzymes in the liver that normally convert ammonia into urea, which is then safely eliminated through urine. Without proper treatment, ammonia can build up to dangerous levels and damage the brain, causing symptoms like confusion, vomiting, lethargy, or in severe cases, seizures and coma.",
    "whoUses": "This code is used by geneticists, metabolic specialists, hepatologists, and pediatricians when a patient has been diagnosed with a urea cycle disorder but the specific type hasn't yet been identified or confirmed. It commonly appears on EOBs when patients are undergoing initial diagnostic testing, genetic counseling, or specialist consultations for suspected ammonia metabolism problems.",
