    "rawCode": "E7222",
    "shortDesc": "Arginosuccinic aciduria",
    "longDesc": "Arginosuccinic aciduria",
    "plainEnglish": "Arginosuccinic aciduria is a rare inherited metabolic disorder where your body cannot properly break down certain amino acids, leading to a buildup of a compound called arginosuccinic acid in your blood and urine. This happens because of a deficiency in an enzyme needed to convert amino acids during the normal process of eliminating nitrogen waste from your body. Symptoms may include developmental delays, intellectual disability, hair loss, liver problems, and growth issues, typically appearing in infancy or early childhood.",
    "whoUses": "Metabolic disease specialists, pediatricians, genetic counselors, and biochemical geneticists use this code when diagnosing and managing children with this inherited condition. It commonly appears in specialized pediatric metabolic clinics and genetic testing centers rather than on routine patient EOBs, as it requires specific genetic screening to diagnose.",
