    "rawCode": "E7223",
    "shortDesc": "Citrullinemia",
    "longDesc": "Citrullinemia",
    "plainEnglish": "Citrullinemia is a rare inherited metabolic disorder where your body cannot properly break down a compound called citrulline, causing it to build up to toxic levels in your blood and urine. This happens because of a defect in one of the enzymes responsible for the urea cycle, which is your body's way of eliminating waste nitrogen from protein metabolism. Symptoms can range from mild developmental delays and learning problems to severe cases with seizures, loss of consciousness, and liver damage, depending on when the condition develops and how severe it is.",
    "whoUses": "Metabolic specialists, pediatricians, geneticists, and neurologists commonly diagnose and manage citrullinemia, particularly in newborn screening programs and genetic counseling settings. This code appears on patient EOBs when genetic testing, metabolic workup, or ongoing management of this inherited disorder is documented.",
