    "rawCode": "E7229",
    "shortDesc": "Other disorders of urea cycle metabolism",
    "longDesc": "Other disorders of urea cycle metabolism",
    "plainEnglish": "This code refers to rare genetic disorders affecting how your body processes urea, a waste product created when your body breaks down protein. When the urea cycle—the metabolic pathway that converts ammonia (a toxic byproduct of protein breakdown) into urea for excretion—doesn't work properly, ammonia can build up in the blood and brain, potentially causing neurological problems, developmental delays, or liver dysfunction. These conditions are inherited and usually appear in infancy or early childhood, though some milder forms may present later in life.",
    "whoUses": "This code is primarily used by metabolic geneticists, pediatricians, and hepatologists when diagnosing and managing patients with rare urea cycle disorders such as argininosuccinic aciduria, citrullinemia, or other enzyme deficiencies. It appears less commonly on routine patient EOBs but may appear when genetic testing, specialty consultations, or hospitalizations for metabolic complications are coded.",
