    "shortDesc": "Non-ketotic hyperglycinemia",
    "longDesc": "Non-ketotic hyperglycinemia",
    "plainEnglish": "Non-ketotic hyperglycinemia is a rare inherited metabolic disorder in which your body cannot properly break down glycine, an amino acid found in protein, causing it to accumulate to dangerously high levels in the blood and cerebrospinal fluid. This buildup damages the brain and nervous system, typically causing severe developmental delays, seizures, muscle weakness, and sometimes life-threatening breathing problems, often appearing in infancy or early childhood. Unlike some other metabolic disorders, this condition does not produce ketones as a byproduct, but the high glycine levels are themselves toxic.",
    "whoUses": "Metabolic geneticists, pediatric neurologists, and neonatologists diagnose and manage this condition, typically in newborns or young children presenting with unexplained seizures and developmental delay. This code appears on EOB statements when genetic testing, brain imaging, or metabolic panel results confirm the diagnosis, though it is relatively uncommon in typical medical billing.",
