    "code": "E72.539",
    "rawCode": "E72539",
    "shortDesc": "Primary hyperoxaluria, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Primary hyperoxaluria, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "Primary hyperoxaluria is a rare genetic disorder in which your body produces too much oxalate, a substance that normally passes through your kidneys and is excreted in urine. When oxalate levels get too high, it can crystallize in your kidneys and other organs, potentially causing kidney stones, kidney damage, and pain. This code is used when you have been diagnosed with primary hyperoxaluria but the specific genetic type (Type 1, 2, or 3) has not been determined.",
    "whoUses": "Nephrologists (kidney specialists) and metabolic disease specialists typically use this code when evaluating and treating patients with high urinary oxalate levels. This code appears on EOB statements when patients undergo genetic testing, kidney imaging, or treatment for kidney stone disease suspected to be caused by oxalate metabolism problems.",
