    "rawCode": "E72540",
    "shortDesc": "Dietary hyperoxaluria",
    "longDesc": "Dietary hyperoxaluria",
    "plainEnglish": "Dietary hyperoxaluria means you have too much oxalate in your urine because of what you eat, not because of a problem with how your body processes it. Oxalate is a substance found in many foods like spinach, nuts, and chocolate, and normally your kidneys filter it out. When you consume too much oxalate-rich food or don't drink enough water, it can build up in your urine and potentially form kidney stones or damage your kidneys over time.",
    "whoUses": "Nephrologists (kidney specialists), urologists, and primary care physicians use this code when diagnosing patients with high urinary oxalate levels caused by diet rather than a genetic or metabolic disorder. This code commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing kidney stone evaluations or urine chemistry testing, particularly when dietary modification is recommended as treatment.",
