    "shortDesc": "Enteric hyperoxaluria",
    "longDesc": "Enteric hyperoxaluria",
    "plainEnglish": "Enteric hyperoxaluria is a condition where your body absorbs too much oxalate from your digestive system, leading to dangerously high levels of this compound in your urine and blood. This typically happens after bowel surgery or in people with inflammatory bowel conditions that affect how their intestines absorb nutrients. When oxalate levels get too high, it can form painful kidney stones and potentially damage your kidneys over time.",
    "whoUses": "Nephrologists (kidney specialists), gastroenterologists, and urologists use this code when managing patients with secondary oxalate accumulation related to intestinal disease or surgery. It appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing evaluation or treatment for recurrent kidney stones or after bariatric/bowel surgeries.",
