    "shortDesc": "Congenital lactase deficiency",
    "longDesc": "Congenital lactase deficiency",
    "plainEnglish": "Congenital lactase deficiency means your body was born without enough lactase enzyme, which is needed to break down lactose (milk sugar) found in dairy products. People with this condition cannot digest milk and dairy properly, leading to symptoms like bloating, cramping, diarrhea, and gas when they consume these foods. This is a lifelong condition that requires avoiding or limiting dairy intake, though lactose-free alternatives are widely available.",
    "whoUses": "Pediatricians and gastroenterologists typically diagnose and manage this condition, usually identifying it in infants and young children when they first consume milk or dairy. This code appears on EOB statements for newborns and children who undergo testing for lactose intolerance or who are diagnosed with milk allergy or digestive issues related to dairy intake.",
