    "longDesc": "Secondary lactase deficiency",
    "plainEnglish": "This means your body has developed a reduced ability to digest lactose (the natural sugar in milk) because of damage to your small intestine from another condition, illness, or treatment—rather than being born with the problem. This can happen after infections, inflammatory bowel diseases, or certain medications damage the lining of your gut, causing symptoms like bloating, cramping, and diarrhea when you consume dairy products.",
    "whoUses": "Gastroenterologists, primary care physicians, and pediatricians use this code when diagnosing lactose intolerance caused by underlying intestinal conditions like celiac disease, Crohn's disease, or infectious gastroenteritis. It commonly appears on EOB statements when patients are evaluated for digestive complaints and the provider determines the lactose intolerance is secondary to another identified condition.",
