    "rawCode": "E7403",
    "shortDesc": "Cori disease",
    "longDesc": "Cori disease",
    "plainEnglish": "Cori disease is a rare inherited metabolic disorder where your body cannot properly break down and store glycogen (a form of stored sugar in muscles and liver). This happens because you lack an enzyme called the debranching enzyme, which causes glycogen to build up abnormally in your liver and muscles, leading to liver enlargement, muscle weakness, and low blood sugar between meals. People with this condition often experience fatigue, delayed growth in childhood, and may have difficulty with physical activity.",
    "whoUses": "This code is used by pediatricians, metabolic specialists, genetic counselors, and hepatologists who diagnose and manage glycogen storage diseases. It appears on EOBs for patients being treated for this genetic condition, typically from childhood onwards, involving genetic testing, specialist consultations, and monitoring for complications.",
