    "shortDesc": "Disorder of fructose metabolism, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Disorder of fructose metabolism, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "This code indicates a problem with how your body processes fructose, a natural sugar found in fruits, honey, and many processed foods. Your body normally breaks down fructose through specific enzymes and metabolic pathways, but when this process doesn't work correctly, fructose can build up in your blood and tissues, potentially causing digestive issues, fatigue, or other symptoms. The 'unspecified' part means your doctor hasn't yet identified which exact type of fructose metabolism disorder you have, or testing hasn't confirmed the specific cause.",
    "whoUses": "Pediatricians, gastroenterologists, metabolic disease specialists, and genetic counselors typically use this code when evaluating children or adults with suspected fructose intolerance or hereditary fructose metabolism disorders. This code is less common on patient EOBs than more prevalent diagnoses, but appears when a patient undergoes testing for digestive issues or metabolic abnormalities related to sugar processing.",
