    "longDesc": "Hereditary fructose intolerance",
    "plainEnglish": "Hereditary fructose intolerance is a rare genetic disorder where your body cannot properly break down fructose, a natural sugar found in fruits, honey, table sugar, and many processed foods. When someone with this condition eats or drinks foods containing fructose, their liver accumulates a harmful substance that can cause severe stomach pain, vomiting, low blood sugar, and serious liver damage if the condition is not managed by strict avoidance of fructose-containing foods.",
    "whoUses": "Pediatricians and geneticists primarily diagnose and manage this condition, as symptoms typically appear when infants are first introduced to fruits or sweetened foods. This code may appear on EOB statements when genetic testing, metabolic workup, or specialized gastroenterology or hepatology consultations are documented for diagnosis or management.",
