    "shortDesc": "Other disorders of intestinal carbohydrate absorption",
    "longDesc": "Other disorders of intestinal carbohydrate absorption",
    "plainEnglish": "Your small intestine has difficulty absorbing certain carbohydrates (sugars and starches) from food, which is not due to lactose intolerance or another well-defined condition. This can happen because your intestinal lining lacks specific enzymes needed to break down or absorb certain carbohydrates, leading to symptoms like bloating, gas, diarrhea, or abdominal pain after eating certain foods.",
    "whoUses": "Gastroenterologists and primary care physicians use this code when evaluating patients with chronic digestive symptoms related to carbohydrate malabsorption. It commonly appears on EOB statements when patients undergo testing for food intolerances or have persistent unexplained digestive complaints.",
