    "code": "E74.810",
    "rawCode": "E74810",
    "shortDesc": "Glucose transporter protein type 1 deficiency",
    "longDesc": "Glucose transporter protein type 1 deficiency",
    "plainEnglish": "Glucose transporter protein type 1 deficiency is a rare genetic disorder where your body cannot properly transport glucose (sugar) from the blood into the brain and other cells that need it. This happens because you're missing or have faulty proteins that act as doorways to let glucose enter cells, which can lead to seizures, developmental delays, movement problems, and a constant feeling of low blood sugar in the brain even when blood sugar levels appear normal. The condition is often managed by following a special ketogenic diet, which provides an alternative fuel source that bypasses the broken glucose transport system.",
    "whoUses": "Metabolic geneticists, pediatric neurologists, and pediatricians diagnose and manage this condition, often in specialized metabolic or epilepsy clinics. This code may appear on EOB statements when patients undergo genetic testing, metabolic workup, or specialist consultations for unexplained seizures or developmental delay, though it is a rare diagnosis that most patients will not encounter.",
