    "plainEnglish": "Tay-Sachs disease is a rare inherited genetic disorder where the body cannot properly break down certain fatty substances in the brain and nerve cells, causing them to build up over time. Infants with this condition typically appear healthy at birth but gradually lose muscle control, vision, and mental function starting around 6 months of age, eventually leading to severe neurological damage. This devastating condition is passed down from parents who each carry one copy of the faulty gene, and currently there is no cure, though treatments focus on managing symptoms and comfort care.",
    "whoUses": "Pediatricians, neurologists, and genetic specialists diagnose and manage Tay-Sachs disease, often in collaboration with genetic counselors. This code appears on EOBs for affected infants and children receiving diagnostic testing, neurological evaluations, and supportive care, though it is relatively uncommon due to the rarity of the condition and carrier screening programs that help prevent births of affected children.",
    "billable": true,
