    "code": "E75.10",
    "rawCode": "E7510",
    "shortDesc": "Unspecified gangliosidosis",
    "longDesc": "Unspecified gangliosidosis",
    "plainEnglish": "Gangliosidosis is a rare inherited metabolic disorder where the body cannot properly break down certain fatty substances (gangliosides) that normally accumulate in nerve cells and the brain. When the specific type isn't identified, it's called unspecified gangliosidosis, which can cause progressive neurological problems ranging from developmental delays and intellectual disability to muscle weakness, vision loss, or seizures, depending on which cells are affected and when symptoms start. This condition is passed down through families in an autosomal recessive pattern, meaning a child must inherit the faulty gene from both parents to develop the disease.",
    "whoUses": "Neurologists, geneticists, and pediatricians use this code when evaluating patients with suspected lysosomal storage disorders or when the precise type of gangliosidosis cannot yet be determined. This code is less common on patient EOB statements because gangliosidosis is extremely rare and often appears only after extensive genetic testing and specialist evaluation; it typically appears in records from specialized pediatric neurology or genetics clinics rather than routine primary care visits.",
