    "rawCode": "E7522",
    "shortDesc": "Gaucher disease",
    "longDesc": "Gaucher disease",
    "plainEnglish": "Gaucher disease is a rare inherited metabolic disorder where your body cannot properly break down a fatty substance called glucocerebroside, causing it to build up in your organs, bones, and bone marrow. This buildup can lead to an enlarged spleen and liver, bone pain and fractures, anemia, and easy bruising—symptoms that typically develop gradually and vary widely depending on which organs are most affected. The condition is caused by mutations in genes you inherit from both parents and cannot be prevented, though treatments are available to help manage symptoms and slow disease progression.",
    "whoUses": "Hematologists, metabolic geneticists, and gastroenterologists most commonly diagnose and manage Gaucher disease through specialized testing and enzyme replacement therapy. While this is a serious chronic condition, it does appear on EOB statements as it requires ongoing specialist care, genetic counseling, and potentially expensive targeted medications.",
