    "rawCode": "E7526",
    "shortDesc": "Sulfatase deficiency",
    "longDesc": "Sulfatase deficiency",
    "plainEnglish": "Sulfatase deficiency is a rare genetic condition where your body cannot properly produce or use sulfatase enzymes, which are proteins needed to break down certain fatty substances in your cells. Without enough of these enzymes, harmful fatty materials build up in your brain, nerves, and other organs, leading to progressive neurological problems such as developmental delays, vision loss, muscle weakness, or cognitive decline depending on which sulfatase enzyme is affected and how severely. This is an inherited metabolic disorder that typically appears in infancy or early childhood and requires specialized treatment and management.",
    "whoUses": "Metabolic disease specialists, geneticists, and pediatric neurologists primarily diagnose and manage sulfatase deficiency. While it is a serious medical condition, this code is less common on routine patient EOBs unless the patient has undergone genetic testing or specialized metabolic evaluation; it appears more frequently in medical records from specialty hospitals and genetic counseling centers.",
