    "rawCode": "E7528",
    "shortDesc": "Canavan disease",
    "longDesc": "Canavan disease",
    "plainEnglish": "Canavan disease is a rare inherited genetic disorder that affects how the brain develops and functions, caused by a deficiency of an enzyme called aspartoacylase. This enzyme is responsible for breaking down certain fats in the brain's protective covering (myelin), so when it's lacking, these fats build up and damage nerve fibers, leading to progressive loss of brain function, muscle weakness, and developmental delays starting in infancy. Symptoms typically include poor head control, developmental regression, seizures, and increasing paralysis as the disease progresses.",
    "whoUses": "Pediatric neurologists and geneticists use this code to diagnose and manage children with Canavan disease, often after genetic testing confirms the diagnosis. While this is a serious genetic condition, it typically appears on EOB statements when families seek genetic counseling, specialized neurological care, or genetic testing rather than on routine office visits.",
