    "shortDesc": "Homozygous familial hypercholesterolemia [HoFH]",
    "longDesc": "Homozygous familial hypercholesterolemia [HoFH]",
    "plainEnglish": "Homozygous familial hypercholesterolemia is a rare genetic condition where you inherit cholesterol-raising genes from both parents, causing your body to produce extremely high levels of LDL cholesterol (the \"bad\" cholesterol) from birth. People with this condition have cholesterol levels that are dangerously elevated and cannot be controlled through diet alone, putting them at very high risk for heart attacks and stroke at a young age. You may develop fatty deposits under the skin (xanthomas) and require aggressive treatment with medications like statins and other cholesterol-lowering drugs, or specialized procedures like apheresis to lower cholesterol levels.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists, lipidologists, and genetic counselors primarily diagnose and manage this condition, as it requires specialized treatment and genetic screening of family members. This code appears on EOB statements for patients receiving genetic testing, cardiology consultations, and specialty pharmacy claims for high-cost cholesterol medications.",
    "billable": true,
