    "shortDesc": "Heterozygous familial hypercholesterolemia [HeFH]",
    "longDesc": "Heterozygous familial hypercholesterolemia [HeFH]",
    "plainEnglish": "Heterozygous familial hypercholesterolemia (HeFH) is an inherited condition where you have one gene copy that causes your body to have very high cholesterol levels from birth. Unlike people who develop high cholesterol from diet and lifestyle, people with HeFH inherit this trait from one parent and have persistently elevated LDL cholesterol (the 'bad' kind) that requires aggressive treatment with medications like statins to prevent early heart disease. You may notice this code on your insurance paperwork because HeFH is one of the most common genetic lipid disorders and usually requires ongoing specialist care and testing.",
    "whoUses": "Cardiologists, lipid specialists, and primary care physicians commonly use this code when diagnosing and managing patients with a family history of early heart attacks or very high cholesterol levels. This code frequently appears on patient EOB statements because individuals with HeFH require regular monitoring, genetic testing, and specialized cholesterol-lowering medications that may be reviewed for insurance coverage.",
