    "plainEnglish": "Hyperchylomicronemia is a condition where your body has abnormally high levels of chylomicrons—tiny fat particles that carry dietary fats through your bloodstream after meals. This happens when your body either produces too many of these particles or has trouble clearing them from the blood, often due to a deficiency in lipoprotein lipase (an enzyme needed to break down fats). People with this condition typically have very high triglyceride levels, which can lead to fatty deposits in the skin and serious complications like pancreatitis.",
