    "rawCode": "E790",
    "shortDesc": "Hyperuricemia w/o signs of inflam arthrit and tophaceous dis",
    "longDesc": "Hyperuricemia without signs of inflammatory arthritis and tophaceous disease",
    "plainEnglish": "You have elevated levels of uric acid in your blood, but you don't currently have gout attacks (the painful joint inflammation) or tophi (chalky deposits of uric acid under your skin). This is a warning sign that your body isn't processing uric acid properly, which can happen due to genetics, diet, certain medications, or kidney issues—and while you're not having symptoms right now, it increases your risk of developing gout in the future.",
    "whoUses": "Rheumatologists, internists, and primary care physicians use this code during routine blood work or preventive care visits when they detect high uric acid levels before gout symptoms develop. It appears on EOB statements when patients have lab findings showing hyperuricemia during screening or follow-up visits, and is important for documenting early intervention opportunities to prevent future gout attacks.",
