    "shortDesc": "Lesch-Nyhan syndrome",
    "longDesc": "Lesch-Nyhan syndrome",
    "plainEnglish": "Lesch-Nyhan syndrome is a rare inherited metabolic disorder that affects how your body breaks down purines (a component of DNA and RNA). This condition causes a buildup of uric acid in the blood and urine, leading to gout, kidney stones, and sometimes severe neurological problems including involuntary movements, intellectual disability, and self-injurious behavior. It primarily affects males and is caused by a deficiency in an enzyme that normally helps recycle purines in the body.",
    "whoUses": "Pediatricians, neurologists, and geneticists typically diagnose and manage Lesch-Nyhan syndrome, often identifying it in infancy or early childhood. This code appears on EOBs less frequently than common conditions, but shows up when a patient with this rare genetic disease is treated for gout, kidney complications, or neurological symptoms related to the syndrome.",
