    "shortDesc": "Myoadenylate deaminase deficiency",
    "longDesc": "Myoadenylate deaminase deficiency",
    "plainEnglish": "Myoadenylate deaminase deficiency is a rare genetic condition where your muscles lack an enzyme needed to break down a substance called adenosine monophosphate (AMP) during energy production. Without this enzyme, your muscles can't efficiently recycle energy during exercise, which may cause muscle cramps, pain, or weakness during or after physical activity. Most people with this condition have mild symptoms that appear during intense exercise, though some may have no symptoms at all.",
    "whoUses": "Metabolic medicine specialists, neurologists, and rheumatologists use this code when diagnosing exercise-related muscle disorders, typically after genetic or muscle enzyme testing reveals the deficiency. This code appears less frequently on patient EOBs since it's a rare genetic condition, but may appear when a patient is evaluated for unexplained exercise intolerance or muscle complaints.",
