    "shortDesc": "Hereditary xanthinuria",
    "longDesc": "Hereditary xanthinuria",
    "plainEnglish": "Hereditary xanthinuria is a rare genetic disorder in which your body cannot properly break down a protein called purine, causing an abnormal substance called xanthine to accumulate in your urine and sometimes form painful kidney or bladder stones. You inherit this condition from your parents (it runs in families), and it happens because you're missing or have a defective enzyme that normally processes purines. Most people with this condition experience recurrent kidney stones, and in some cases, xanthine crystals can damage the kidneys over time.",
    "whoUses": "Nephrologists (kidney specialists), geneticists, and urology specialists diagnose and manage hereditary xanthinuria. This code is more common in medical charts and specialist records than on routine patient EOBs, but may appear if a patient has genetic testing or presents with kidney stone complications related to this condition.",
