    "longDesc": "Hereditary erythropoietic porphyria",
    "plainEnglish": "Hereditary erythropoietic porphyria is a rare inherited blood disorder where your body can't properly break down a substance called heme (which makes blood red). This causes toxic chemicals called porphyrins to build up in your blood and tissues, leading to severe blistering and scarring of sun-exposed skin, discolored teeth and urine, and sometimes hemolytic anemia where red blood cells break down too quickly. Patients typically experience these symptoms starting in early childhood and must avoid sunlight.",
