    "rawCode": "E801",
    "shortDesc": "Porphyria cutanea tarda",
    "longDesc": "Porphyria cutanea tarda",
    "plainEnglish": "Porphyria cutanea tarda is a rare metabolic disorder where your body cannot properly process porphyrins (natural substances needed to make hemoglobin in blood), causing them to build up and damage your skin. The main symptoms are blistering, fragile skin, and severe sun sensitivity on exposed areas like your hands and face, often triggered or worsened by sunlight exposure, alcohol use, or certain medications. This is the most common type of porphyria and is typically triggered by factors like liver disease, hepatitis C, or HIV infection.",
    "whoUses": "Dermatologists and hematologists most commonly diagnose and manage this condition, though gastroenterologists may be involved if liver disease is the underlying cause. This code does appear on patient EOBs when treatment or workup for skin symptoms related to porphyria is provided, though the diagnosis itself is relatively uncommon.",
