    "code": "E80.4",
    "rawCode": "E804",
    "shortDesc": "Gilbert syndrome",
    "longDesc": "Gilbert syndrome",
    "plainEnglish": "Gilbert syndrome is a common, mild, and lifelong condition where your liver doesn't process bilirubin (a yellow substance produced when red blood cells break down) as efficiently as it should. This causes bilirubin to build up in your blood, sometimes making your skin and eyes slightly yellowed (jaundiced), especially during stress, illness, fasting, or intense exercise. The good news is that Gilbert syndrome is harmless and requires no treatment—it's just how your liver naturally works, and you can live a completely normal life with it.",
    "whoUses": "Primary care physicians, hepatologists (liver specialists), and gastroenterologists diagnose and monitor Gilbert syndrome, typically after finding elevated bilirubin levels on routine blood work. This code commonly appears on patient EOBs when laboratory work is ordered to investigate jaundice or unexplained elevated bilirubin.",
