    "shortDesc": "Crigler-Najjar syndrome",
    "longDesc": "Crigler-Najjar syndrome",
    "plainEnglish": "Crigler-Najjar syndrome is a rare inherited liver disorder where the body cannot properly process a yellow pigment called bilirubin, causing it to build up in the bloodstream and tissues. This leads to jaundice (yellowing of the skin and eyes), and in severe cases, can damage the brain if bilirubin levels get too high. The condition is present from birth and occurs because the liver lacks an enzyme needed to break down and eliminate bilirubin effectively.",
    "whoUses": "Pediatricians, neonatologists, and hepatologists (liver specialists) use this code most commonly, as Crigler-Najjar syndrome typically manifests in newborns and infants. While it is a serious genetic condition, it may appear on patient EOB statements primarily when families receive care at specialized treatment centers or during phototherapy and monitoring appointments.",
