    "code": "E80.7",
    "rawCode": "E807",
    "shortDesc": "Disorder of bilirubin metabolism, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Disorder of bilirubin metabolism, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "Your liver normally processes a waste product called bilirubin, which gives bile its color and helps your body get rid of old red blood cells. When something goes wrong with this process—whether it's how your liver handles bilirubin, how it's transported in your blood, or how it's excreted—bilirubin can build up in your body, potentially causing jaundice (yellowing of the skin and eyes) or other problems. This code is used when doctors know you have a bilirubin metabolism problem but haven't pinpointed the exact type or cause.",
    "whoUses": "Hepatologists, gastroenterologists, and primary care doctors use this code when patients present with jaundice or abnormal liver function tests suggestive of a bilirubin processing disorder. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing liver testing or hospitalization for unexplained jaundice, though more specific bilirubin disorder codes are preferred when the exact diagnosis is identified.",
