    "shortDesc": "Hereditary hemochromatosis",
    "longDesc": "Hereditary hemochromatosis",
    "plainEnglish": "Hereditary hemochromatosis is an inherited genetic condition where your body absorbs and stores too much iron from the food you eat. Because your body has no natural way to eliminate excess iron, it builds up over time in organs like the liver, heart, and pancreas, potentially causing serious damage including cirrhosis, heart problems, and diabetes. People with this condition often have no symptoms early on, but screening and treatment with blood iron tests and iron-removal therapies can prevent complications.",
    "whoUses": "Primary care physicians, gastroenterologists, and hematologists typically diagnose and manage hereditary hemochromatosis through genetic testing and iron level monitoring. This code appears on EOBs when patients have genetic testing, iron studies, or specialist consultations related to iron overload management.",
