    "shortDesc": "Familial hypophosphatemia",
    "longDesc": "Familial hypophosphatemia",
    "plainEnglish": "Familial hypophosphatemia is a hereditary condition where your body cannot properly maintain adequate phosphate (a mineral essential for bone strength and energy production) in your blood. This inherited disorder is typically caused by genetic mutations that affect how your kidneys handle phosphate, leading to low phosphate levels that can result in weak or soft bones, especially in children, along with pain or deformity. You may inherit this condition from one or both parents, and it often requires lifelong management with phosphate supplementation and vitamin D therapy.",
