    "shortDesc": "ABCC6 deficiency causing pseudoxanthoma elasticum",
    "longDesc": "ABCC6 deficiency causing pseudoxanthoma elasticum",
    "plainEnglish": "This is a rare genetic disorder where your body lacks a protein called ABCC6, which normally helps manage minerals and calcium in your tissues. Without this protein, calcium builds up abnormally in elastic fibers—the stretchy components of your skin, blood vessels, and eyes—causing them to become stiff and brittle. People with this condition may develop yellowish bumpy skin, vision problems, and potentially serious complications with blood vessels and the heart.",
    "whoUses": "Geneticists, dermatologists, ophthalmologists, and cardiologists use this code when diagnosing or managing pseudoxanthoma elasticum. It typically appears on EOB statements for specialized genetic testing, genetic counseling, ophthalmology evaluations, or cardiology follow-ups rather than routine primary care visits.",
