    "shortDesc": "CD73 deficiency causing arterial calcification",
    "longDesc": "CD73 deficiency causing arterial calcification",
    "plainEnglish": "CD73 deficiency is a rare genetic disorder where your body lacks an enzyme called CD73, which normally helps prevent calcium from building up in your arteries. Without this enzyme, calcium accumulates abnormally in your blood vessel walls, causing them to harden and narrow—a condition called arterial calcification. This can reduce blood flow and increase your risk of heart disease and stroke.",
    "whoUses": "This code is primarily used by cardiologists, geneticists, and metabolic disease specialists when evaluating patients with premature arterial calcification or when CD73 deficiency has been confirmed through genetic testing. It rarely appears on standard patient EOBs as it is an extremely rare inherited metabolic disorder; most patients would see it documented in specialist cardiology or genetics clinic notes.",
