    "shortDesc": "Meconium ileus in cystic fibrosis",
    "longDesc": "Meconium ileus in cystic fibrosis",
    "plainEnglish": "Meconium ileus is a serious intestinal blockage that occurs in newborns with cystic fibrosis, where the baby's first stool (meconium) becomes abnormally thick and sticky due to defective pancreatic secretions, preventing it from passing normally through the intestines. This condition typically appears within the first few days of life and requires urgent medical intervention, which may include enemas, medication, or surgery to clear the blockage. Babies with cystic fibrosis have thick, sticky mucus throughout their body, and this same problem affects their digestive system, making it one of the first signs that a newborn might have this genetic condition.",
    "whoUses": "Neonatologists, pediatric surgeons, and pediatric gastroenterologists use this code when managing newborns with cystic fibrosis who develop meconium ileus. This code commonly appears on newborn hospital bills and insurance explanations of benefits, as it typically requires hospitalization and specialized treatment in the first weeks of life.",
