    "longDesc": "Mixed disorder of acid-base balance",
    "plainEnglish": "A mixed disorder of acid-base balance means your blood has more than one type of pH imbalance happening at the same time. Normally, your body carefully controls how acidic or alkaline your blood is through your lungs and kidneys, but when multiple problems occur together—such as both too much acid and too much alkalinity in different parts of your system—it creates a complex imbalance that's harder to treat. Patients with this condition may experience fatigue, confusion, shortness of breath, or other symptoms depending on which specific acid-base problems are occurring.",
    "whoUses": "This code is primarily used by intensivists, nephrologists, pulmonologists, and emergency medicine physicians in hospital and critical care settings, as mixed acid-base disorders typically occur in seriously ill patients. It is less common on routine patient EOBs but may appear for patients with significant chronic kidney disease, severe respiratory conditions, or recent critical illness.",
