    "plainEnglish": "Hyperkalemia means you have too much potassium in your blood. Potassium is an important mineral that helps your heart, muscles, and nerves work properly, but when levels get too high, it can cause serious problems like irregular heartbeats, muscle weakness, or dangerous changes in how your heart functions. This condition can develop from kidney disease, certain medications (like ACE inhibitors or diuretics), dehydration, or tissue damage, and it usually requires prompt medical attention to bring potassium levels back to normal.",
    "whoUses": "Emergency medicine physicians, cardiologists, nephrologists (kidney specialists), and intensive care physicians commonly diagnose and treat hyperkalemia in hospital or urgent care settings. This code appears frequently on EOB statements when a patient has been treated in an emergency department or hospital for dangerously elevated potassium levels, as it represents an acute medical condition requiring immediate intervention.",
