    "plainEnglish": "Hypokalemia means your blood potassium level is abnormally low. Potassium is a critical mineral that helps your heart beat regularly, controls muscle contractions, and maintains proper nerve function—so when levels drop too low, you might experience weakness, muscle cramps, irregular heartbeat, or fatigue. This can happen due to medications (like water pills or certain blood pressure drugs), vomiting or diarrhea, kidney disease, or eating disorders.",
