    "longDesc": "Transfusion associated circulatory overload",
    "plainEnglish": "Transfusion-associated circulatory overload (TACO) is a reaction that can occur when someone receives a blood transfusion and their body receives too much fluid too quickly, overwhelming the heart's ability to pump it effectively. This causes the blood to back up in the veins and lungs, leading to symptoms like shortness of breath, chest discomfort, high blood pressure, and rapid heart rate—typically developing during or shortly after a transfusion. It's a preventable complication that doctors watch for carefully, especially in patients with heart or kidney problems.",
