    "code": "E88.01",
    "rawCode": "E8801",
    "shortDesc": "Alpha-1-antitrypsin deficiency",
    "longDesc": "Alpha-1-antitrypsin deficiency",
    "plainEnglish": "Alpha-1-antitrypsin deficiency is a genetic condition where your body doesn't produce enough of a protein called alpha-1-antitrypsin, which normally protects your lungs and liver from damage. Without adequate levels of this protective protein, you're at high risk for developing emphysema (a type of chronic lung disease), liver disease, and other complications—especially if you smoke or are exposed to lung irritants. People with this condition may experience progressive shortness of breath, chronic cough, and wheezing as lung damage accumulates over time.",
    "whoUses": "Pulmonologists (lung specialists), hepatologists (liver specialists), and primary care physicians commonly diagnose and manage this condition, often after detecting it through blood tests or genetic screening in patients with early-onset emphysema or unexplained liver disease. This code frequently appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing genetic testing, lung function studies, or receiving augmentation therapy (infusions of replacement protein).",
    "billable": true,
    "isNew": false,
    "isRevised": false,
