    "code": "E88.10",
    "rawCode": "E8810",
    "shortDesc": "Lipodystrophy, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Lipodystrophy, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "Lipodystrophy is a condition where your body has abnormal fat distribution—meaning some areas may have too little fat while others have too much, or fat may be completely absent from certain regions. This can happen due to genetic factors, metabolic disorders, or certain medications (like some HIV treatments), and it can affect how your body processes energy and stores nutrients. You might notice uneven fat deposits, changes in your appearance, or metabolic problems like high blood sugar or cholesterol.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists, internal medicine doctors, and infectious disease specialists commonly use this code when evaluating abnormal fat distribution, particularly in patients with metabolic disorders or those on certain medications. It appears on EOB statements when lipodystrophy is documented but the specific type or underlying cause hasn't been definitively identified.",
