    "shortDesc": "Partial lipodystrophy",
    "longDesc": "Partial lipodystrophy",
    "plainEnglish": "Partial lipodystrophy is a condition where your body loses the ability to maintain normal fat deposits in certain areas, leading to an uneven or abnormal distribution of fat under the skin. You might notice that some parts of your body (like your face, arms, or torso) appear to have little to no fat, while other areas may have excess fat or remain normal. This condition can occur due to genetic factors, autoimmune problems, or sometimes as a side effect of certain medications, and it may affect how your body processes insulin and cholesterol.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists, dermatologists, and internists commonly diagnose and manage partial lipodystrophy, particularly when metabolic complications like insulin resistance or diabetes develop. This code appears on EOB statements when patients seek treatment for the condition or its metabolic consequences, though it is relatively uncommon.",
