    "plainEnglish": "HIV-associated lipodystrophy is a condition where people living with HIV experience abnormal changes in how their body distributes fat. Some areas may lose fat (becoming thin, especially in the face, arms, and legs) while other areas gain excess fat (particularly around the abdomen, chest, or back of the neck). This happens as a side effect of certain HIV medications or the virus itself, and can affect how a person looks and feels, as well as increase risk for metabolic problems like high cholesterol and diabetes.",
