    "code": "E88.811",
    "rawCode": "E88811",
    "shortDesc": "Insulin resistance syndrome, Type A",
    "longDesc": "Insulin resistance syndrome, Type A",
    "plainEnglish": "Insulin resistance syndrome Type A is a metabolic condition where your body's cells don't respond properly to insulin, a hormone that regulates blood sugar. In Type A insulin resistance, this problem is due to genetic or autoimmune factors that affect how insulin attaches to and works with your cells—rather than from lifestyle factors like obesity. People with this condition typically have very high insulin levels, difficulty controlling blood sugar, and may develop diabetes if not managed.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists and internal medicine doctors use this code when diagnosing patients with rare genetic or autoimmune forms of insulin resistance. It occasionally appears on patient EOBs, particularly when patients have undergone specialized metabolic testing or are being evaluated for unusual metabolic disorders.",
