    "code": "E88.819",
    "rawCode": "E88819",
    "shortDesc": "Insulin resistance, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Insulin resistance, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "Insulin resistance means your body's cells aren't responding well to insulin, a hormone that helps move sugar from your bloodstream into your cells for energy. When this happens, your pancreas has to work harder and produce more insulin to get the job done, which can eventually lead to high blood sugar levels and type 2 diabetes if left untreated. You might not notice any symptoms at first, but over time insulin resistance can contribute to weight gain, fatigue, and increased risk of heart disease.",
    "whoUses": "Primary care physicians, endocrinologists, and cardiologists commonly use this code when evaluating patients with metabolic syndrome, prediabetes, or unexplained high blood sugar. It frequently appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing diabetes screening or metabolic workups, and is often documented alongside weight management or preventive care visits.",
