    "shortDesc": "Postprocedural hypothyroidism",
    "longDesc": "Postprocedural hypothyroidism",
    "plainEnglish": "Postprocedural hypothyroidism means your thyroid gland isn't producing enough thyroid hormone after you had surgery or another medical procedure—most commonly after thyroid surgery, radioactive iodine treatment, or radiation to the neck. Without adequate thyroid hormone, your metabolism slows down, which can cause fatigue, weight gain, cold sensitivity, and dry skin. This condition requires lifelong thyroid hormone replacement therapy, usually taken as a daily pill.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists, general surgeons, and otolaryngologists (ENT doctors) use this code when treating patients whose hypothyroidism resulted from intentional or accidental thyroid damage during procedures like thyroidectomy or thyroid cancer treatment. This code commonly appears on EOB statements for patients receiving ongoing thyroid medication management and monitoring after these procedures.",
